{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17564046","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17564046"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:09:07+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:09:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16931"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16931","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16931"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.06,0.21,0.51,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9621"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67809"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9621","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9621"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16931"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53274"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"152"},{"type":"tags","id":"2967"},{"type":"tags","id":"4043"},{"type":"tags","id":"4550"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"4985"},{"type":"tags","id":"6344"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"12802"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22705"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43670"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67809","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/67809"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 56-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with worsening urinary incontinence over the past two weeks. She reports a long history of occasional leakage with coughing or exercise, but recently has developed frequent urinary urgency with episodes of incontinence before reaching the toilet. She also notes increased frequency and nocturia. She has a medical history of three vaginal deliveries and mild asthma. Her only regular medication is salbutamol inhaler as needed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Abdominal examination reveals mild suprapubic tenderness. There is no palpable bladder. Cough stress test demonstrates small volume urine leakage.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate first investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Post-void residual ultrasound","Bladder and renal tract ultrasound","Urodynamic studies","Midstream urine microscopy, culture and sensitivity","Three-day bladder diary"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features of mixed urinary incontinence (both stress and urge symptoms) with an acute deterioration. The presence of frequency, urgency, and suprapubic tenderness raises the possibility of a urinary tract infection, which can exacerbate underlying incontinence.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMidstream urine microscopy, culture and sensitivity\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate first investigation as urinary tract infection is a common, treatable cause of acute worsening of incontinence symptoms. Treatment of an infection may resolve the acute deterioration and allow better assessment of the underlying incontinence.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPost-void residual ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E is an important investigation in the assessment of incontinence to exclude overflow incontinence, but it should be performed after excluding infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBladder and renal tract ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E would be indicated if there were concerns about structural abnormalities or complications, but is not the first-line investigation for uncomplicated incontinence.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrodynamic studies\u003C/strong\u003E are specialised tests that may be helpful in planning management of complex or refractory incontinence, but they are not first-line investigations and should only be performed after excluding infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThree-day bladder diary\u003C/strong\u003E is useful for documenting patterns of fluid intake, voiding, and incontinence episodes, but it is not the first priority given the acute change in symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe basic evaluation of urinary incontinence includes history, physical examination, urinalysis, post-void residual volume measurement, and bladder diary. However, when there is an acute change in symptoms, infection should be excluded first as it is a readily treatable cause of symptom exacerbation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Urinary tract infection can exacerbate both stress and urge incontinence symptoms and should be excluded first.","Mixed urinary incontinence presents with features of both stress and urge incontinence.","Basic investigations for incontinence include urinalysis, post-void residual volume, and bladder diary before specialist referral."],"references":["Moore EE, Jackson SL, Boyko EJ, Scholes D, Fihn SD. Urinary incontinence and urinary tract infection: temporal relationships in postmenopausal women. Obstet Gynecol. 2008 Feb;111(2 Pt 1):317-23. doi: 10.1097/AOG.0b013e318160d64a. PMID: 18238968.","Nandy S, Ranganathan S. Urge Incontinence. [Updated 2022 Sep 19]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK563172/#"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53274"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16931"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"ite